<section id="basics" class="active">
<h2>What Is Dental Hygiene?</h2>

<div class="card">
<p>
Dental hygiene involves keeping the teeth, gums, and mouth clean to prevent disease.
When plaque (a sticky layer of bacteria) builds up, it can harden into tartar and
cause serious oral and systemic health problems.
</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3> What Is Plaque?</h3>
<p>
Plaque is a colorless film of bacteria that forms on teeth every day.
If plaque is not removed through brushing and flossing, it produces acids that
damage tooth enamel and irritate the gums.
</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3> What Is Tartar?</h3>
<p>
Tartar (also called calculus) is hardened plaque. Once plaque becomes tartar,
It cannot be removed at home and must be cleaned by a dental professional.
</p>
</div>
</section>


<section id="cleaning">
<h2>Cleaning, Whitening & Gum Care</h2>

<div class="card">
<h3> Proper Brushing Technique</h3>
<ul>
<li>Brush twice a day for two minutes minimum </li>
<li>Clean the gums gently</li>
<li>Use gentle circular motions</li>
<li>Do not scrub aggressively to prevent bleeding</li>
<h3> Flossing & Gum Cleaning</h3>
<ul>
<li>Floss once daily to remove plaque between teeth</li>
<li>Slide floss gently under the gumline</li>
<li>Do not snap the floss directly into the gums</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3> Teeth Whitening: Safe vs Unsafe</h3>
<ul>
<li>Safe: Whitening fluoride toothpaste, dentist-approved whitening strips, water filter to prevent excessive hard water contact</li>
<li>Unsafe: Citric juices, baking soda overuse, excessive hard water usage</li>
<li>Excessive whitening can damage enamel and increase sensitivity</li>
</ul>
</div>
</section>


<section id="diseases">
<h2>Diseases Linked to Poor Dental Hygiene</h2>

<div class="card">
<h3> Gingivitis</h3>
<p>
Gingivitis is the earliest stage of gum disease. Symptoms include red, swollen,
and bleeding gums. It is reversible with proper brushing and flossing.
</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3> Periodontitis</h3>
<p>
If gingivitis is left untreated, it can develop into periodontitis.
This causes permanent damage to the gums and bone, leading to tooth loss.
</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3> Heart Disease (Endocarditis)</h3>
<p>
Bacteria from infected gums can enter the bloodstream and attach to damaged
areas of the heart, causing a serious infection known as endocarditis.
</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3> Diabetes Complications</h3>
<p>
Poor oral health can make it harder to control blood sugar levels.
At the same time, diabetes increases the risk of gum disease.
</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3> Mental Health Effects</h3>
<p>
Chronic dental problems can cause pain, embarrassment, and anxiety, negatively
affecting self-esteem and confidence (especially targeting teens/tweens) and even adults.
</p>
</div>
</section>



<section id="myths">
<h2>Dental Hygiene Myths</h2>

<div class="card">
<h3>Myth 1: Sugar is the only cause of cavities</h3>
<p>
Fact: While sugar contributes to cavities, plaque and bacteria, poor brushing habits,
and certain medical conditions also play a major role.
</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3>Myth 2: Brushing harder cleans better</h3>
<p>
Fact: Aggressive brushing can damage enamel and gums, even causing them to bleed. Gentle circular motions are more effective and even safer. 
</p>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3>Myth 3: Mouthwash can replace brushing</h3>
<p>
Fact: Mouthwash can help reduce bacteria, but it cannot remove plaque and food debris like brushing and flossing.
</p>
</div>
</section>



